    <h2 class="nhsuk-u-margin-top-6">
    When to use this pattern
    </h2>
    <p>
    A-Z lists are great to categorise a large number of pages under one subject, but they only work when users know the name of the thing they're looking for, and that it sits under the specific subject. 
    </p>
    <p>
    We've found users preferring an A-Z list of pages over search. In testing we've seen users chose to use the A-Z because they were not sure they could spell a medical term such as 'appendicitis' to search for it, but expected to find it in the A-Z.
    </p>

    <p>
    NHS.UK currently uses A-Z on the following subjects:
    </p>
    
    <ul>
	<li><a href="https://www.nhs.uk/conditions/">Conditions</a></li> 
	<li><a href="https://www.nhs.uk/medicines/">Medicines</a></li>
    </ul>

    <h2>
    When not to use this pattern
    </h2>
    
    <p>Don't use the A-Z pattern:</p>

    <ul>
	<li>to group non-related subject pages</li>
	<li>as part of a transactional service</li>
  <li>as part of a content page</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Elements of the A-Z pattern</h2>

        <h3>
    A-Z navigation
    </h3>

