    <h2 class="nhsuk-u-margin-top-8">
      Research on this pattern
    </h2>

    <p>
    The mini-hub pattern was created to work on NHS.UK conditions pages.
    </p>

    <p>
    While developing the pattern, we ran 3 rounds of research with users, including those with disabilities and people with low digital literacy on Age-related macular degeneration.
    </p>

    <p>
    The pattern was also reviewed by the Digital Accessibility Centre.
    </p>

    <p>
    In testing, the structure and labelling of the pages fitted the mental model of all users, helping them to understand the structure of the content. 
    </p>

    <p>
    Users found the active link formatting on the menu helpful in knowing where they are. Some users felt that the links (in the content list) helped them understand what information there is, and choose what is relevant to them.
    </p>

    <p>
    The majority of users we tested with, including a user with very low digital skills - used pagination to navigate through pages and knew this was associated with the contents list at the top of the page. 
    </p>

    

